WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standard reference for ISO/WD 24942, which standardises the
specification parameters for cameras and image sensors used in machine
vision. It defines measurement methods and reporting formats for key
performance metrics, ensuring comparability across devices.

WHY IT EXISTS
Machine vision cameras lack a uniform datasheet standard, making it
difficult to compare sensitivity, noise, and speed. ISO 24942 harmonises
these specifications using EMVA 1288‑based methods, extending them for
industrial and AI vision. GIOP adopts it to certify machine vision
sensors within its body profiles.

HOW IT WORKS
The standard prescribes measurement protocols and formulas for quantum
efficiency, read noise, dynamic range, dark current, and geometric
accuracy. Key formulas are provided below; the full procedure is in the
standard itself.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Industrial inspection, robotics, autonomous vehicles
- GIOP sensor metrology (Kingdom 02)

WHO USES IT
L1 Architects certifying machine vision sensors; L2 Engineers developing
machine vision pipelines.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Enables apples‑to‑apples comparison of machine vision cameras by providing
standardised metrics defined through auditable formulas.

KEY FORMULAS

1. Quantum Efficiency (QE)
   QE(λ) = μ_e / μ_p
   μ_e = average electrons collected per pixel per exposure
   μ_p = average incident photons per pixel per exposure

2. Read Noise
   N_read = σ_dark  (standard deviation of dark signal at minimum exposure)

3. Dynamic Range
   DR = 20 * log10( FWC / N_read )  [dB]
   FWC = full well capacity (electrons)

4. Dark Current
   D = ( μ_e_dark / t_int )  [e‑/s]
   where μ_e_dark is mean dark signal at exposure time t_int.

5. Signal‑to‑Noise Ratio
   SNR = μ_e / sqrt( μ_e + N_read² + D * t_int )

6. Geometric Accuracy (e.g., pixel pitch)
   Pixel_pitch = sensor_width / N_active_pixels_horizontal

